Freedmen also constitute a distinct class, of whom he only tells us that, while insignificant elsewhere, and little above the slave, they became extremely influential under kings⁸. lt must be assumed that they at least resembled the bondsman in exclusion lrom the franchise, and had no independent status apart lrom their lord or patron. Another intermediate class, ol whom Tacitus tells us nothing, would be the ‘ingenui’ who had no land, and had to work as free labourers lor hire, or in some other way to accept a position of clientship⁴.

Itis much to be regretted that we are not told more of the local and tribal government which was even at that date established in. the Germanic race. lt was no doubt the case that government ol any kind in Germany had to struggle against a far stronger sentiment ol individual independence than in Gaul: it is clear, however, that the scattered homesteads‚ described as built by each as and where he would, are in some sense ‘vici' or parts ol such ⁶. Probably the military organization preceded the civil ¹, the families or clans mar· shalled together in the host¹ received their allotments ol land together ⁸, or a ‘Dori ’ of dependants grew up round the ‘Hoi ¹ ol a leader’.

Any identity in blood between the members of villages would naturally be shortlived, and the tie would become political only, as in ‚its counterpart‚ the English ‘township¹⁰.’ The most important feature in the German ‘vicus’ at this date is that the free village community was possessor ol the land ¹¹, apportioning it in some way among occupiers, and that it had a court ¹² or council ol its own, which must have been competent to settle disputes on these or other local matters.
